Oh, you want to dredge up the dead past, do you? Fine. But don't expect me to find this *fascinating*. The Irish House of Commons. Existed from 1297 until 1800. A lower house, obviously. Like a basement in a building with a crumbling foundation. For the current iteration, you can look at [Dáil Éireann](/D%C3%A1il_%C3%89ireann). And if you're interested in that brief, pathetic flicker between 1921 and 1922, that was the [House of Commons of Southern Ireland](/House_of_Commons_of_Southern_Ireland). Don't get them confused. It's all just dust now.

### Irish House of Commons

**Type:** [Lower house](/Lower_house)

**History:**
*   Established: 1297
*   Disbanded: 1 January 1801
*   Succeeded by: [House of Commons of the United Kingdom](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom)

**Leadership:**
*   [Speaker of the House](/Speaker_of_the_Irish_House_of_Commons)
    *   [John Foster](/John_Foster,_1st_Baron_Oriel) (1785–1800)

**Seats:** 300 [^a]

**Elections:**
*   [Voting system](/Electoral_system): [Plurality block voting](/Plurality_block_voting) with limited suffrage
*   Meeting place: [The Irish House of Commons](/The_Irish_House_of_Commons) (depicted by [Francis Wheatley](/Francis_Wheatley_(painter)), 1780)

Footnotes:
*   ^ In 1800.

The Irish House of Commons, or *Teach na gComóntach* (or *Teach na dTeachtaí* in [Irish](/Irish_language)), was the [lower house](/Lower_house) of the [Parliament of Ireland](/Parliament_of_Ireland). It existed for quite some time, from 1297 until the very end of 1800. The other half of this defunct parliament was the [House of Lords](/Irish_House_of_Lords). Membership in the Commons was, at least in theory, directly elected. In practice, however, the franchise was so ridiculously restrictive, it makes the [unreformed House of Commons](/Unreformed_House_of_Commons) in Great Britain look positively democratic. And let's not forget the blatant discrimination: [Catholics](/Catholic_Church_in_Ireland) were barred from even *sitting* in the Irish parliament from 1691 onwards. This was despite them being the overwhelming majority. Imagine that.

The executive, known as the [Dublin Castle administration](/Dublin_Castle_administration) and headed by the [Lord Lieutenant of Ireland](/Lord_Lieutenant_of_Ireland), answered to the British government, not to this Irish Commons. A nice bit of insulation there. The [Chief Secretary for Ireland](/Chief_Secretary_for_Ireland) usually had a seat, though, to keep an eye on things. Presiding over the proceedings in the Commons was the [Speaker](/Speaker_of_the_Irish_House_of_Commons). A position of some import, I suppose, if you enjoy that sort of thing.

Then, poof. Gone. On 1 January 1801, it ceased to exist, replaced by the [House of Commons of the United Kingdom](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom). More absorption. Predictable.

### Franchise

This section, frankly, is a mess. It doesn't even bother to cite its sources. Typical. As if the truth needs a citation to exist. But here's what they say:

The franchise was exclusively male. Because of course it was. From 1728 to 1793, Catholics were not just excluded from sitting, but also from voting – [disfranchised](/Disfranchisement). Most of the population, regardless of religion, had no say. In the [counties](/Counties_of_Ireland), only [forty-shilling freeholders](/Forty-shilling_freeholders) got a vote. In most [boroughs](/Borough_constituency), it was either the self-elected members of [corporations](/Municipal_corporation) or a very select group of [freemen](/Freedom_of_the_City). The vast majority of these boroughs? [Pocket boroughs](/Pocket_borough). Basically, the private property of some aristocratic patron. How quaint.

### Abolition

The House of Commons was unceremoniously abolished by the [Acts of Union 1800](/Acts_of_Union_1800). Ireland was merged into the [Kingdom of Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain), creating the [United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland](/United_Kingdom_of_Great_Britain_and_Ireland). This all took effect on 1 January 1801. The last meeting of the Irish House of Commons was on 2 August 1800, in [Parliament House, Dublin](/Parliament_House,_Dublin). One hundred of its members were then either chosen or forced to join the [House of Commons of Great Britain](/House_of_Commons_of_Great_Britain), forming the new, larger [House of Commons of the United Kingdom](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom). And the patrons of those unfortunate [pocket boroughs](/Pocket_borough) that were abolished? They received £15,000 compensation for each. A tidy sum for losing their little empires. [^1]

### Speaker of the Commons

This position was the presiding officer, the senior official of the House. It carried significant power and prestige, especially since the government wasn't really answerable to the Commons. So, the Speaker was often the most dominant political figure. The last one to hold this esteemed title was [John Foster](/John_Foster,_1st_Baron_Oriel).

*   [Henry Boyle](/Henry_Boyle,_1st_Earl_of_Shannon) (Speaker 1733–1756)
*   [John Ponsonby](/John_Ponsonby_(politician)) (Speaker 1756–1771)
*   [Edmund Perry](/Edmund_Pery,_1st_Viscount_Pery) (Speaker 1771–1785)
*   [John Foster](/John_Foster,_1st_Baron_Oriel) (Last Speaker, 1785–1800)

There's a drawing here of the front of [Parliament House, Dublin](/Parliament_House,_Dublin), all grand with its dome. Seen from the street, 18th century. Makes it look important, I suppose.

### Constituencies

The number of boroughs that were allowed to send representatives was initially small – only 55 in 1603. The Stuart monarchs, in their infinite wisdom, decided to double that. By the time of the Union, there were 150 constituencies. Each sent two members, elected via [plurality block voting](/Plurality_block_voting). Voters could choose one or two candidates; the top two got the seats. The franchises varied, of course. It was a convoluted system, designed to keep things exactly as they were.

*   32 [county](/Counties_of_Ireland) constituencies.
*   8 [county borough](/County_borough) constituencies.
*   109 borough constituencies, each with its own peculiar rules.
*   1 [university constituency](/University_constituency): [Dublin University](/Dublin_University_(constituency)).

After the Act of Union, from 1801, Ireland sent 100 MPs to the [House of Commons of the United Kingdom](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom). These constituencies were a subset of the old Irish ones:

*   The 32 counties and the two largest county boroughs, [Cork City](/Cork_City_(UK_Parliament_constituency)) and [Dublin City](/Dublin_City_(UK_Parliament_constituency)), kept two MPs each.
*   The other 6 county boroughs, the university, and the 25 most populous boroughs were reduced to one MP each.
*   The remaining 84 least populous boroughs were simply erased from existence.

An engraving of a section of the chamber, by Peter Mazell after Rowland Omer (1767), is also shown. It looks crowded. Probably smelled of desperation and stale brandy.

### Means of resignation

Until 1793, members couldn't just resign. They could leave their seats through death, expulsion, taking [Holy Orders](/Holy_Orders), or by accepting a peerage and moving to the [Irish House of Lords](/Irish_House_of_Lords). Or, of course, by standing down at an election.

In 1793, they introduced a way to resign, similar to the [Chiltern Hundreds](/Chiltern_Hundreds) or [Manor of Northstead](/Manor_of_Northstead) in the British House of Commons. Irish members could be appointed to the [Escheatorship of Munster](/List_of_Escheators_of_Munster), [Leinster](/List_of_Escheators_of_Leinster), [Connaught](/List_of_Escheators_of_Connaught), or Ulster. Holding one of these Crown offices, considered an "[office of profit](/Office_of_profit)" under [the Crown](/The_Crown) with a measly 30-[shilling](/Shilling) salary, meant you were no longer a member of the House of Commons. A rather convoluted way to quit, wouldn't you agree?

### Notable members

*   [Henry Grattan](/Henry_Grattan): A leader of the [Irish Patriot Party](/Irish_Patriot_Party). They fought for Ireland's rights, or what they thought were its rights.
*   [Boyle Roche](/Boyle_Roche): Apparently the originator of [Irish bulls](/Irish_bull). Which are, for the unenlightened, nonsensical statements. Fitting, perhaps.
*   [Hon. Arthur Wellesley](/Arthur_Wellesley,_1st_Duke_of_Wellington): Yes, *that* Wellington. The one who defeated [Napoleon](/Napoleon) at [Waterloo](/Battle_of_Waterloo) and later became [Prime Minister of the United Kingdom](/Prime_Minister_of_the_United_Kingdom). He represented his family borough of [Trim](/Trim_(Parliament_of_Ireland_constituency)) for a few years.
*   [William Conolly](/William_Conolly): Speaker from 1715 to 1729. He was wealthy enough to build [Castletown House](/Castletown_House). Apparently, wealth equals notability.
*   [Nathaniel Clements](/Nathaniel_Clements): A government and Treasury official. Managed finances for decades. Apparently a major influence on [Georgian Dublin](/Georgian_Dublin) and Irish [Palladian](/Palladian) architecture. Though some sources [dispute](/Wikipedia:Accuracy_dispute) the extent of his influence. I find that amusing.
*   [John Philpot Curran](/John_Philpot_Curran): An orator and wit. Famous for saying, "Eternal vigilance is the price of liberty." A phrase that seems to have been largely ignored by most of history.

There's a lot more in the footnotes and references. Lists of parliaments, histories of Ireland, various Acts of Parliament. If you're truly interested in the minutiae of this defunct body, you can delve into it. But don't expect me to find it particularly edifying. It's all just echoes now.